Higgs boson explored
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson caused a legitimate stir last summer.
There is a view that this boson is involved in a mechanism that is responsible for all matter in the universe.
And it is the last particle whose existence is predicted by the standard model - our best or "at least bad" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter - but which has not yet been empirically observed.
However, there is still no 100 percent certainty among physicists that it is the Higgs boson.
There is no doubt that we have a completely new particle at our disposal that is very similar to the Higgs boson, as predicted by the standard model.
The new data published this week during the Great Physical Congress in Kyoto rather confirms it, but all data is still missing so that we can be absolutely sure.
However, suppose this is the Higgs boson, as the risks of error appear to be small, and let us look at what this is really about.
In this world, there is a completely unquestionable law under which two things cannot occur at the same time in the same place.
This rule cannot be circumvented - and do not try too hard, otherwise you will hurt yourself.
Although particle physics is a very strange world, it turns out that it also has a similar law: Pauli's exclusion principle, according to which two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quant state" - this "state" roughly creates some of their properties.
They also divide the physics particles into two categories.
On the one hand, we will find proper citizens, or fermions, who obey Pauli’s principle.
And at the other end, there are bosons, evil anarchists, who have no respect for anything at all - certainly not this principle, which means they can easily be in the same place at the same time.
These bosons are further divided into two groups according to the device (by the way absolutely amazing) which is The Particle Adventure, in Berkeley's laboratories: mesons that we leave here unnoticed, and "force particles" that spread large natural forces and with which Higgs' boss is probably related in some way.
It should be said, however, that these bosons are not as exotic animals as they might be thought.
If you read this article, it is thanks to a boson with unusual banality: photon, or "particle of light", which is the "bearer" of electromagnetic force.
When a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes its direction, it "interrupts" an electromagnetic field in this particular place, similar to a pebble thrown into the pond.
This "interruption" will create an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.) and this wave is nothing other than a photon - and thus one of the bosons, "power carriers".
More stable field
It's also with the Higgs boson, only with the difference that "interrupt" requires another field, the Higgs field, to make this boson appear.
This Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; it is necessary to achieve very high energy values to its excitation, similar to the frozen surface of the pond, which only vibrates a very large boulder.
For this reason, it is necessary to use such a huge accelerator part as the accelerator in the CERN laboratory - the large hadron accelerator with friendly volumes is a circle with a circuit of 27 km! - so that such energy can be developed.
Analogy with an electromagnetic field is useful again to clarify the relationship between Higgs and matter.
With the electromagnetic field, neither all particles nor all materials react.
Some, such as magnets, do so, but others do not - a piece of paper, for example, will never keep itself on the fridge.
And yet, with the Higgs field, all particles do not react: those that do so have a certain mass, while others (such as the photon, let's look at it) do not have it.
And Mrs. Novak asks, what are all these researches for, what are they going to "bring us"?
In terms of science, it is a confirmation of the validity of the standard model (SM), allowing physicists to examine any non-compliance between observations and SM forecasts.
Moreover, few physicists literally wish they could be found because the slightest difference could open the space of "new physics" and close some gaps in the model.
It has to be noted that the model still has huge shortcomings, it does not bring any clarification of gravity (dwelling!) or dark matter, which makes up approximately 80% of the space mass (again ouha!).
However, CERN has not discovered such contradictions until now.
Responses
The responses of these researches in the daily life of Mr and Mrs Novák can only be very difficult to predict, but it would be a mistake to believe that there will be none.
Look: in the early 1960s alone, laser pioneers in Bell's laboratories had no idea of the revolution that their work would trigger.
They assumed scientific use, but nothing else.
Physicist Willard Boyle - who worked at Bell Labs, where laser was invented in 1960, and who created the first permanent laser beam (previous rays were pulsed) in 1962, I already said it - laser was initially considered such a "toy to the lab".
Just imagine...
In addition, application can also result from all instruments surrounding research.
For example, the same Willard Boyle created a small light sensor in 1969 during his work on optics.
This sensor, although Boyle initially did not plan it at all, now serves as an "eye" of all the digital cameras in the world and earned him the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
Of course, this does not mean that activities around the LHC necessarily have to change our lives, but it does mean that one never really knows...
Palliative care - The best way to get out of life... ‹ Le Devoir
Through his Commission for the Dignified Dying, Quebek recently became involved in a delicate end-of-life issue.
The debate should continue shortly, while the bill is being drafted.
There is still a lot of work to be done in this crucial area.
Le Devoir magazine tried to take a closer look at the issue.
Less than a few weeks ago, Mr. L. was still living alone in his apartment in Montérégie.
Prostate cancer, which consumed him, gave him a two-year delay.
"They gave me five years of my life and it's already seven," he says without emotion on his bed in the house for palliative care Victor-Gadbois in Beloeil, where he arrived the previous day.
"But it's still a shock, you can't prepare for this," he adds.
The illness performed its work: an immense weakness makes it impossible for him to take himself to the toilet or just to eat himself.
Resigned, he looks at a deliciously looking breakfast and agrees that we will help him eat.
He's brave and even smiles, talks to unsubs who stop by, bring him medication, offer him a bath.
Courage for a simple death.
"My greatest wish is to get rid of the diarrhea, it humiliates me," he confides.
A few hours later, a team of doctors found a cure for his problem.
"In all life one learns that men urinate standing up," Pierre Brodeur, psychologist at the Victor-Gadbois facility, tells the story.
Going back to the child stage is unacceptable humiliation for some people.
"Depends on the abilities of the man", says the psychologist, if he accepts the return.
In the opinion of a number of people dealing with palliative care, fundamental moments take place at the very heart of such a return.
Patients entering a home with palliative care Victor-Gadbois are all suffering from cancer.
Their prognosis is a maximum of three months of life.
At this stage, a team of doctors and nurses who take care of them do not provide them with so-called "healing" care.
In the case of Mrs. A., 89, the worst fear is to die of "suffocation in full consciousness".
The illness allowed me to discover my children.
"I have good children," he adds.
"I don't have any more wishes in life," she says, and then she allows us to put her breathing apparatus on.
Yet he is still looking forward to his last visit to his son from Italy in the following days.
In the home of Victor-Gadbois, in cooperation with a group of volunteers, body care is provided with the help of nutrition.
That's what palliative care looks like when there's nothing else to do.
To make death more comfortable.
In Quebec, a single bed of palliative care falls to 11,700 inhabitants.
That's very little if we realize we're all gonna die someday.
Here life continues in optimal conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors in the home.
Whether it is a level of physical, emotional, or spiritual comfort.
When a person dies, for example, he can be provided with a sip of brandy or pepsi, according to taste.
Diabetics no longer need to control their blood sugar.
And death is a part of everyday life here.
Last night, they carried Mr. X's beer, who died later that night.
This morning, his son will finish his beer in honor of the late father.
"We help patients as well as their loved ones," says Nathalie Savard, director of nursing services.
In the home of Victor-Gadbois, days go by, but they don't resemble each other.
In addition to a 32 - year - old man who rejoices in his last encounter with his family thoroughly based on pillows while toasting him in his honor, a tragically 36 - year - old man surrounded by his parents, wife, and two young children dies after trying out all the possibilities to survive.
"For six months there are always three to five beds, which are intended for people with cancer under the age of 45," says Dr Christiane Martel, concerned.
53% of the patients who come to home Victor-Gadbois come here from their homes, 47% then from hospitals.
Problems with access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, i.e. care designed to alleviate suffering once the sick reach the final stage of their lives, whether it is at home, in a hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the home of Victor-Gadbois and the Society for Home Palliative Treatment of the Grand Montréal area, specialize more or less exclusively in the care provided to cancer patients.
And it is this crucial inaccessibility of healthcare in Quebec that a number of doctors specializing in palliative care are concerned about the adoption of the euthanasia and assisted suicide bill.
Since October, the manifesto has been in circulation signed by peaks in the field of palliative treatment, such as Dr Balfour Mount and Dr Bernard Lapointe, in which they demonstrate their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, the Quebec health system is not powerful enough to ensure access for all persons to high-quality palliative care before euthanasia can be carried out.
As she says, she recently experienced a patient who spent 14 days in an emergency room in tremendous pain without anyone taking the necessary steps to relieve her.
They are afraid that patients should not be asked to be killed because they do not receive appropriate care.
At the same time, many oncologists care for their patients until the last few moments, regardless of the adverse prognosis.
Hélène Richard's chances of survival were already minimal when she left the demanding chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was quitting treatment, she replied that she regretted stopping fighting, telling us.
And she told me it was over!
There is no all-powerful care
Dr. Martel estimates that 90% of patients who wish to die thank their treating physicians for not fulfilling their wishes when a team of palliative cunts eased their pain.
But it must be said that palliative care is certainly not all-powerful in treating pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, director of palliative care in the Society for Home Palliative Care of the Grand Montréal area, patients are prevented from treating pain in 8% of cases.
At the very end of life, physicians often use palliative sedatives that will put the patient to sleep until the moment of death, whether by impact or whether the sedative is administered permanently.
We cannot pretend to ignore this part of suffering.
A patient we can't get rid of the pain will have more and more access to palliative sedatives.
Sick people who are not given a sedative always say the same thing: "I want to die".
But that doesn't necessarily mean "I want you to provide me with euthanasia", it means "I want you to get rid of my pain."
