In the case of Bitcoin, all network nodes are depositories of current accounts books, controllers, money issuers and buyers as well as sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users actually takes place between two e-mail addresses.
However, the user may choose a different address for each payment, thereby ensuring anonymity.
The set of information related to this transaction is electronically signed by a dual key encryption system.
The network can thus verify the validity of the transaction.
Furthermore, thanks to the file content, it is possible to ensure that exchanged bitcoins exist in the public book of current accounts that is distributed throughout the network.
The key phase is to write this new transaction into this book.
It is done by solving the mathematical task assigned to computers, whose solver, a temporary central banker, will have the right to complete this additional line.
This is a phase of file cutting; i.e. the transformation of a huge file into a shorter and unique digital imprint.
Computers will "take over" this new transaction and add a number to it, only then they will "cut apart".
The goal is to find a number that provides a specific print (a lot of zeros at the beginning).
Once this number is found, the other knots will easily check its accuracy.
The transaction is then indestructibly displayed connected to a string of all other transactions; any modification would change the print.
If the user wanted to pay twice with the same money very quickly in a row (within ten minutes), the network will confirm only one of the two transactions - the other will be abandoned because each one has a different print.
The computer that solves the challenge wins 50 bitcoins.
In order to avoid inflation, this remuneration is regularly divided by two, probably by the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is thus limited by 21 million, but they can be divided up to 100 millionths, so there is room for margin...
The difficulty of the assigned task is also increased with the increasing level of calculation.
The network has experienced its ups and downs.
