Difficult Work at the Egyptian Constitution
President Muhammad Morsi embarked on another poker game.
While Egypt remains the most divided in its history due to the proclamation of the constitution, which temporarily confers on it unlimited powers, it decided to play vabank.
On Wednesday, he announced, regardless of everyone else's opinion, that the Constitutional Assembly would approve the final text tomorrow.
Less than a week ago, the head of state granted this assembly another two months to complete the necessary work.
For nearly two years, Egypt has been using a provisional text that has been added many times, weakening the country’s constitutional stability and leading to legal conjectures.
This new initiative has only further strengthened the country's diversity.
From the opposition's point of view, the President remains in his 'autocratical delirium', continuing to 'violate his word' and 'stepping the law'.
However, its supporters assure that it is a means of turning the constitutional and political crisis as quickly as possible and speeding up the transitional process.
A referendum should be held in two weeks.
This is a very short period of time that will force the Brotherhood to withdraw from the intention of clarifying the article to the Egyptians.
It is also a way for the President to regain national and democratic legitimacy, while the entire country is being swept away by protests.
As confirmed in an interview for American weekly Time, Muhammad Morsi seems convinced the Egyptians would vote in favour.
Especially because this hastily organized vote puts the Egyptian people ahead of the ultimatum: 'You either approve my text or I keep unlimited powers', which should otherwise end after the adoption of the new constitution.
And in this particular atmosphere yesterday, 85 Members of the said Constitutional Assembly approved the text with a large majority of Islamists.
Most liberals were absent in the vote.
In mid-November, not long before the constitution was announced, they slammed the door saying they didn't have a chance to assert their views.
Human rights advocates, civil society or members of religious minorities imitated their move.
In order to achieve a quorum, 11 alternates were quickly added yesterday morning.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
It is not surprising, then, that the articles of the constitution were often voted unanimously.
The commentators continued to consider that one of the few disputes revolved around that day... prayer hours when some committee members held the view that the hours in the meeting room were not properly adjusted.
The text voted on last night consists of 234 articles.
The subject of general attention, Article 2, remains ultimately identical to the 1971 version of the constitution and states that "the principles of Sharia law are the main source of law".
Salafist parties, for whom the introduction of Islamic law is one of the fundamental requirements, hoped to replace the term 'principles' with the term 'rules', allowing for stricter application.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been corrected represents a sign of their goodwill and respect for other parts of Egyptian society.
"The Hypocrisy", the liberals object, who see it only as a rhetorical problem.
According to them, the Islamization of the constitution takes place through other articles.
They focus in particular on Article 220, which confers an advisory role on the University of al-Azhar, in particular on issues of compliance checks with Sharia law.
According to Egypt's expert Sophie Pommier, it is disturbing because "persons authorized to express are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
It can be seen as the beginnings of theocracy".
The fears of liberals are further fueled by the fact that the next rector of the university should be less moderate than the current one.
"For now, no particular religious consequence has been manifested.
With this constitution, Egypt remains a framework civil state.
Most lawyers who worked on this text are not ulama, but university workers, many of whom have graduated in French schools," temperate concern Alexis Blouet, who is preparing a job on the constitutional transition in Egypt.
They agree, however, that "there may be contradictions regarding the interpretation of Article 220, because in it the terms used belong to the religious dictionary.
There is particularly a reference to "fiqh" [Islamic legal science, note red.].
And there may be a question in the future to what extent civil judges are competent to comment on it".
Yesterday's approved text is, in addition to religious sites, highly criticized because of the extended powers granted to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood insists that there has been significant restrictions on them compared to the former regime.
Another disputed place: powers vested in the military.
In accordance with the wishes of military representatives, the verification of the defence budget will not be carried out by Parliament, but by the National Defence Council.
Furthermore, in military courts, proceedings with civilians will not be banned, as the Human Rights Association demanded.
These associations speak of their doubts in connection with the text, which they believe is directed against freedom.
The act of blasphemy is maintained and the insult continues to be prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, especially for the press.
Moreover, no article deals with the protection of women, stressing Heba Morayef of the Human Rights Watch organization.
According to her, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture referred to in Article 36.
This word was not mentioned in the previous constitution.
While the President of Egypt was scheduled to appear in a television speech last night, manifestos are scheduled for this afternoon.
The supporters of the head of state will then manifest on Saturday.
