Poland and the cosmos.
Last week at the meeting of the ministers of the European Space Agency countries, Poland was accepted as the twentieth member of this European Space Agency, as the second country from the former Eastern Bloc countries (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of the ESA on November 12, 2008).
Poland began close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and participated in a number of Agency projects over the years.
However, Poland’s journey to space began much earlier.
Polish enthusiasts had taken flight to space before World War II; but they did not always meet with understanding.
For example, I will recall the lecture by A. Sternfeld at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory, which featured ideas from his pioneering work Entry to Space.
The ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the listener cold and after years Sternfeld recalled that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
Sternfeld in 1934 won the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirscha Prize for the Entry into Space in France.
Recalled Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became a great promoter of astronomy and cosmonautics.
In Polish journals he published hundreds of articles and wrote a number of books devoted to these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski became a world-renowned promoter of cosmonautics and his contribution was also appreciated by the fact that one of the craters on the averted side of the Moon was named by his name.
As early as 1925, a railway dresser was built in Poland, which was to be fitted with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, the author of the proposal is not known and there are no details of the project.
It is not even clear whether the rocket was to be used for the running of the drezina or for its braking.
Information about this drezín is only known from the period press.
From 1933, Polish artillery began to tackle missile missiles.
Research was provided by Komorka Techniki Ubrozenia in cooperation with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfk and Prof. Gustaw Mokrzyckiegi.
It is evident from surviving materials that research has reached the stage of practical tests.
However, by the arrival of German troops, research was interrupted.
In 1937, the design of a photoelectric fighter rocket, designed by engineer Rohoziński, appeared in the professional press, and the following year the work of Rakiet - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza autor Leliwa-Krzywoblocký came out.
Both projects were intended for military use of rocket engines.
Just before the war, all projects of military use of missile technology were devoted to the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy), which all work was coordinated.
The committee was founded in 1937, but after two years of activity his activities ended the start of the war.
Other works dedicated to cosmonautics appear after the Polish press war thanks to the work of the Polish astronaut society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time, there is a mention of the company in the November edition of the 1954 edition of Problemy magazine, in which there are four more comprehensive articles dedicated to astronautics.
In one of them, by Prof. M. Subotowicze, it is proposed to create a society that will deal with cosmonautics.
At the time, projects of artificial satellites were already underway and it was clear that space research was a promising field.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronaut Society (PTA) has sought to join the International Astronaut Federation (founded 1951) and already in the autumn, PTA became a full member.
And in the following year, the first PTA chairman Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959) became vice chairman of the International astronaut Federation.
He held this post until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, PTA has been significantly involved in the development of a very successful weather rocket RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which became the first Polish rocket to undertake scientific research.
The first type of RM-1 was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
The rocket with a range of 1800 metres was about 80 cm long and its weight was less than 5 kg.
Later, an improved version of RM-1A was built, and in the summer of 1959 flight tests of a two-stage RM-2 rocket were started in the Bledov Desert.
The rocket was 1.4 metres long and its weight was about 11.5 kg.
Another development type should have been able to do real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket was to have a range of up to 14.5 km and its task was to monitor the high wind.
However, in 1962, further developments were suspended.
Following the first RM-type rockets, the Meteor-1 rocket developed from 1962 to 1965.
The rocket was designed as two-stage, its total length was 510 cm and the starting weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types (marked Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) have been developed, which differed in size of the space for scientific instruments.
In the Meteor-1A rocket, a space of 0.4 litres, a 0.34 litre Meteor-1B, and a 0.62 litre Meteor-1C were available.
The maximum range for all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket developed at the Aviation Institute, whose first flight trials began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had a starting weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a payload of 10 kg to a height of around 60 km.
Subsequently, the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
It is still important to mention Poland's entry into COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the creation of the COSPAR National Committee two years later.
Poland also participated in space research on Soviet artificial satellites as part of the Intercosmos programme, and in 1978, the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remek.
