Toughest craft in the world: sulfur carriers in Kawah Ijen volcano
For four euros, carriers in the area of Indonesian volcanoes gamble with their life and health as they withstand 70 kilos of sulphur down steep stone paths.
There are people for whom their work is hell, and there are those who literally work in hell.
This is the case with Anta Wijayi, one of the 400 miners who earn their living by conquering sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
Because of this, it has to flail every day to the bottom of the crater, where sulphur gases escape from the inside of the Earth and when in contact with the air, it goes into a solid state.
After cutting out large blocks of sulphur, which together weigh up to 70 kilos, it carries them on its shoulders in two bamboo baskets along steep stone paths.
The peak of the volcano, which rises 2,386 metres, is only 250 metres, but it takes the exhausted carriers over 40 minutes to rise at a turtle pace up because they maintain balance and carefully reconsider their steps to not slip and collapse into the abyss.
They know that any stumbling could cost them their lives, as it happened to a French tourist who crashed from Kawah Ijen rocks years ago.
Miners in Kawah Ijen earn five cents for every kilo of sulfur they extract
When they are at the top, they travel around tourists who photograph them as if they were monkeys in the circus, and they tirelessly carry heavy weight baskets, which the mining company placed slightly lower, at an altitude of 1850 metres.
It is a PT Candi Ngrimbi company that has been mining in the volcano since 1960 and has never paid its workers more than 662 Indonesian rupees (five cents) per kilo of sulphur.
It is then sold for 10,000 rupees (83 cents) to the petrochemical industry, as this mineral has its place in everyday life and is used for the production of matches, fun pyrotechnics, cosmetics, dynamite and even for the bleaching of sugar.
"Because it is commonly carried 70 kilos, we earn about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) per trip," Anto, who usually travels three trips a day, explains.
One trip takes him three hours and at the end he is devastated, but he can earn 138,000 rupees (11.5 euros) per day.
Although this seems to be a negligible amount for such inhuman efforts, it is three times what he would have made in the field.
"The daily wage of miners is very high here. For example, 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) per day are paid for coffee collection, and the salary in two weeks is two million rupees (167 euros)," explains the carrier, who previously worked on Bali as a bricklayer on the tourist island.
There was his salary of 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) per day and the work was not as heavy, but Anto returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a village near the volcano, for a serious reason that is as convincing in Indonesia as sulfur: "I married a young girl from Bali who is Hindu, and I took her to Java to convert to Islam."
Anto has asthma, he has trouble breathing, he still coughs, and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases.
At the age of 27, Anto three times a day risks life in the Kawah Ijen volcano, whose sulfur has already started to collect its toll on him, even though his face is protected by a special mask and glasses.
He's got asthma, he's having trouble breathing, he's still coughing, and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases that escape from the volcano.
That's the price he has to pay to achieve his dream.
"I will work for two more years because I want to open a shop or study Spanish or French," he promises more than decent English.
This sympathetic and intelligent young man affected by fate could be a tourist guide, waiter or receptionist at the hotel, and instead does the work of a porter.
