What is private offline is both private and online
Privacy.
According to the dictionary published by the Royal Spanish Academy, this is something that has a personal character or "an area of private life that everyone has the right to protect against any disruption".
What is privacy for a person under the age of 16?
How does it apply this definition in its daily life and social media?
Does he understand the dangers he is exposed to when he publishes things on the Internet that he would certainly not tell anyone in normal communication?
Journalists from elPeriódico interviewed five boys and girls between 10 and 15 years old who are frequent Internet users.
In four cases, they considered the term privacy to be "something entirely of their own" on a personal level and as a "user name and password" if it was social networks.
"I wouldn't disclose my biggest secret," says ten-year-old Jorge in an effort to explain the importance of privacy in places like Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail and Windows Live Messenger, where he has had accounts for two years.
"They are very secret secrets, my mom may know about them, but not the whole world," she claims.
"I put nice pictures or pictures of us playing on FB.
I'm talking to friends there, too.
I wouldn't share a photo that wasn't mine, or a photo that would mock someone," she says.
This boy realizes that it is wrong to publish obscene photographs, photographs of naked persons or photographs of crimes, or to write humiliating or rude comments.
Jorge says he knows all 35 friends he has on FB and his nine supporters on Twitter.
Most of them are related.
Among them is a mother who has the name and password of one of the accounts.
"I started a Twitter account to express my opinions and write interesting posts.
I don't know if anyone will answer me, I'm just putting them there," he adds.
"Social networks are fun, I can talk to relatives who are far or fast to communicate with friends," he says.
Without hesitation, he says he would never accept a request from an unknown person.
He wouldn't even care if someone recommended an unsub.
The case of 14-year-old José is different.
This teenager owns accounts on Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask networks, and at the latest mentioned network admits that he does not know 20 people from his friend list.
"I'm not afraid of this because we have something in common, such as music," he says.
According to this boy, none of them were directing him or asking him for an address or phone number.
"If they push me or demand me, I will simply remove them from my account," he admits.
José applied to Ask after reading a recommendation on Twitter.
This boy is not a stranger's experience with what is today called cyberbullying.
"A friend of mine was blackmailed on a social network.
They threatened him and asked for money.
He never knew who it was," he confirms.
According to José, the victim didn't check out of the account.
"Just activated a private regime."
It then explains a series of steps how to securely set the account.
Unlike Jorge, this boy would publish photos of acquaintances in unpleasant or embarrassing situations.
"Of course I would if someone bothered me or I just wanted to.
Even though I know it's cyberbullying," he says.
Key Questions
Marielos Porrasová, an English teacher and graduate in the field of Education and Teaching, believes that children and adolescents need to understand that the main goal of these networks is to inform them correctly.
It states that: "Internet originated as a means of finding information, but when social networks appeared, the rules of the game changed."
Marrielos Porrasová notes that academic Marc Prensky, a graduate of pedagogy at Yale University and author of the article Digital Aboriginals and Digital Immigrants, introduced these terms to explain this phenomenon.
"Digital natives are children and young people born at the time of this technology.
We are digital immigrants who have to teach them, and yet we are learning ourselves," he says.
It explains that this is a complex topic, "because we ask them to discern what is appropriate to spread, publish and say, and what is not, at an age when they are not yet ripe for it".
Also, to be discreet about the surroundings, at a time when what they desire most is to be popular, to have thousands of friends and not to think about the consequences", he adds.
According to this specialist, the most effective way to show children and adolescents what privacy is, asking questions that make them think.
"Telling them not to do anything doesn't work," he adds.
Next, Marrielos Porras lists some of the possibilities: Are there things you wouldn't tell a stranger, so why do you do it on the Internet?
Or, would you like someone to post your picture the way you posted your friend's?
You know what other people publish about you?
When you mark the persons in the photos from the celebrations, did you ask these persons for permission?
And one more: do everyone always need to know what you're doing?
The next point is to make them realize that they have to behave in the Internet environment as well as outside of it.
They're the same rules.
"Man follows respect, morality and other principles outside the Internet, and it should be the same on social networks," he claims.
Supervision
Estuardo Guardia, a university professor, first degree teacher, and educational advisor explains the need for children's parents to carefully read the rules of social networks.
"If they understand every insidious thing, they have a good basis for talking to their children about the consequences they may have of setting up an account on the Internet.
