When religion professor Stuart Charmé decided to take an end-of-the-world course this semester, he knew it was an irresistible lure: The end of the "long number" of the Mayan calendar, which is due to come on December 21, has caught many people as proof that the end of the world is coming.
But Charmé had no idea what was ahead of him in the next few months: Catastrophe Hurricane Sandy, a budget gap that some call "the debt Armageddon", and the growing conflict into which Israel is drawn, a place in which, according to Christians theorizing about the end of the world, the Apocalypse will begin.
